title: For Sale:  Iver Johnson DA top break 38 S&W revolver , 1904
postcontent:
In need of financial backing to put a down payment on a house. Unfortunately the only thing I own worth money is my firearms. I am only interested in cash sales, no trades.  

I will meet you at the Blacksburg shooting range if you would like to test fire any of my listed firearms. May consider meetings at local "gun friendly" businesses, like a gun shop. I will not meet you at my home or yours, unfortunately there are some folks out there wanting to do harm and we do not have the time to "get to know" one another. Hate to do this but you will need to provide your own ammo for test fires. Seems that folks like to make me drag all my guns out, haul them to the range, shoot up my ammo and then not buy anything. Ammo and gas ain't cheap so do not waste my time. 

Federal law dictates you must be a VA resident and of legal age. Bill of Sale will be provided with each purchase. 

Firearms are priced at what I have invested and there is no room for haggling. 

More pictures at:
http://s647.photobucket.com/user/Roanoker494/library/Iver%20Johnson%20Safety%20Model%202 

Up for your consideration is a Iver Johnson top break safety model 2 built in 1904. This hammerless revolver is designed to fire the 38 S&W round loaded with black powder, use of modern smokeless powder can result in damage to the firearm and/or injury to the user. The 38 S&W round IS NOT the same as any other 38 ammo available. There are no manufacturers producing the correct ammo but all the needed components are available to load your own. Starline and Remington make the brass, Missouri bullets cast the proper lead bullet, the brass use regular magnum small pistol primers and you can load with your choice of black powder or pyrodex. The rounds I have fired used FFFg Pyrodex pistol powder. All said and done you could load your first batch at .50 a round, .30 a round after that since you already have the brass. 

This revolver indexes well, has a good bore and appears to have been used very little over the 110 years it has been on this earth. The only noted external blemishes are flaking nickel plating and minor rust, overall the metal is very smooth and could be easily replated if desired. Noted internal blemishes include lead build up in the rifling, minor bore pitting and the trigger return spring is broken.

title: For Sale/Trade:  M1 Garand
postcontent:
Make me an offer

This is a great example of what a battle rifle should be. The M1 Grand, the greatest battle implement ever created. The barrel and receiver match July-august 1944. receiver s/n 3091xxx. Barrel drawing #1-S-A-8-44. This was the first step I made in vetting this rifle, Further research from various websites and books by M1 Garand expert Scott A. Duff the bolt is March 1944, the trigger group is November 44, the op rod is Oct 42 - Dec 43. The barrel and receiver has all the correct proof marks along with the correct cartouches. On the left side of the stock there is a number painted on it, A34. From talking to vets I know they informed that when they were issued a rifle for the day, week, and so on they had to give the armory they're weapons card. Once they returned the rifle they would get the card back. On this card was the matching rack number in this case this rifle sat on 'A' rack in slot 34. I will provide all the research and documents to the buyer, I also found on eBay a weapons card, unfortunately the card is not for this rifle, (I wish it was). I called the CMP and spoke with the master armorer, he confirmed all of my findings, in my notes is his number and extension. I have tested the head space with the Herters "go", "no go" and field gauge. The rifle has passed all three gauges. I also bought an M1 Garand tool from eBay. It Measures various things in the Winchester and Springfield rifles, one of which is the muzzle diameter, to test whether or not the barrel is "shot out". The barrel and bore are clean and tight. I have taken this rifle as far as I can with the research, now it is time to sell it. It was a fun project, now on to the next one. All offers will be entertained.
